"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The approach we have taken to support households impacted by welfar</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e reform does have to contend with some significant challenges</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> going forward</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  For example, the initial period of the implementation of welfare reform has been during the spring and summer and households intending to "stay and pay" have not had to factor i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n additional costs such as heating and winter clothin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">g.  The housing solutions our HWRT </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">explore with households are restricted to properties offered at current local housing allowance rates which, in reality, only provide access to 20% of the local housing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> market. The most significant challenge for many local authorities responding to welfare reform, and in trying to meet housing need overall, is the investment in and the supply of new affordable housing for households who cannot find a sustainable local ho</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">using solution in the market.  We understand this is a wider issue than that under consideration by the committee, however, we feel it is something that should also be borne in mind as a contributory factor.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol s